message.content:
The start symbol expands as  

S → NT10 NT16,  

so the very first token of any generated string comes from NT10.  
NT10 has exactly one production:

NT10 → NT15 NT2

Hence the first tokens are produced by NT15, followed by the tokens of NT2.

Tracing NT15:

NT15 → NT22 NT21  
NT22 → NT27 NT21

Therefore the order of the first few tokens produced by NT15 is

(1) tokens of NT27  
(2) tokens of an NT21 (call it NT21₁)  
(3) tokens of another NT21 (call it NT21₂)

NT27 is lexicalised:

NT27 → 't2'

Thus the very first token generated by the grammar is necessarily the terminal t2 – which matches the first symbol of the given string.

The second token of the string must be the first token produced by NT21₁, so we have to check whether NT21 can ever begin with the terminal t19 (the second symbol of the string).

NT21 → NT20 NT30,  
so its first token is the first token produced by NT20.

NT20 has the two possible binary rules

NT20 → NT17 NT4  
NT20 → NT21 NT28 .

In the first case the first token comes from NT17; in the second case it again comes from an NT21 (creating the same sub-problem recursively).  
So it suffices to ask whether NT17 can ever start with t19.

But NT17 expands only by

NT17 → NT26 NT2 | NT4 NT3 | NT34 NT7 | NT31 NT30,

and the first symbols derivable from the left-hand children are

NT26 → 't27'  
NT4   → 't32' or 't34' (or non-terminals that in turn start with those)  
NT34 → starts with either 't34' or 't27'  
NT31 → 't14'.

None of these possibilities yields t19 as the first terminal. Consequently NT17, and therefore NT20 and NT21, can never start with t19.

Hence after the initial t2 produced by NT27 it is impossible for the grammar to produce t19 immediately next. The required prefix t2 t19 of the target string cannot be generated, so the whole string cannot be in the language of the grammar.

No

To be produced by the grammar the string has to come from  

S → NT10 NT16 with NT10 → NT15 NT2.

That means the first part of every derivation is the word generated by NT15, immediately
followed by the word generated by NT2.

Step 1 – what NT15 can end with  
NT15 → NT22 NT21  
 NT22 → NT27 NT21  (NT27 ⇒ ‘t2’)  
 NT21 → NT20 NT30, and NT30 is a terminal non-terminal with the only possibilities  
  NT30 ⇒ ‘t26’ or NT30 ⇒ ‘t28’.  
So, regardless of how the inside of NT20 expands, the *last* token produced by NT15
is necessarily either ‘t26’ or ‘t28’.

Step 2 – what NT2 can start with  
The first rule–symbols of every NT2-derivation are the left child of one of its four
binary rules

 NT2 → NT30 NT27  (first token ‘t26’ or ‘t28’)  
 NT2 → NT22 NT14  (first token ‘t2’)  
 NT2 → NT33 NT7  (first token ‘t32’)  
 NT2 → NT28 NT3  (first token ‘t34’ or ‘t27’)

Hence the very first terminal coming from NT2 can only be one of  
 ‘t26’, ‘t28’, ‘t2’, ‘t32’, ‘t34’ or ‘t27’.  
It can **never** be ‘t12’.

Step 3 – look at the given string  
… t2 t27 t27 t27 t28 t12 …

The fifth token is ‘t28’, i.e. one of the two tokens with which NT15 must finish.
Consequently the sixth token (‘t12’) would have to be the first token produced
by NT2 – but, as just shown, NT2 can never start with ‘t12’.

Therefore no parse tree for the string can exist in the grammar, and the string is **not** in the language generated by it.

No
